      },
      "lineNbr": 36,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-28T21:33:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This isn’t right. We’re using ucontext_t as the native CPU context type on iOS regardless of architecture, because ucontext_t is the type we use with signal handlers. When desktop macOS exists for ARM, we would use an out-of-process Mach exception handler, so we’d use a Mach context type and not ucontext_t.\n\nSummarizing:\n\nMac and not iOS: x86 uses x86_thread_state (and nothing else is defined yet)\niOS: always use ucontext_t",
      "revId": "fbc3fd552020e02915cb8485c64d3ebe42bb2bd3",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
